'''Benjamin Zimmer''' (born 1971)<ref name=UChicago>{{cite news |author=Steven Yaccino |title=Away with words |work=University of Chicago Magazine |url=http://magazine.uchicago.edu/1106/features/away-with-words.shtml |date=May-June 2011 |accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[linguist]] and [[lexicographer]]. He is the executive producer of the Visual Thesaurus and Vocabulary.com. He was the "On Language" columnist for [[The New York Times Magazine]] from March 2010 to February 2011 and formerly a research associate at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]'s Institute for Research in Cognitive Science and an editor of American dictionaries at [[Oxford University Press]].

==Career==

Zimmer graduated from [[Yale University]] in 1992 with a [[bachelor of arts|B.A.]] degree in linguistics, and went on to study linguistic anthropology at the [[University of Chicago]].<ref name=UChicago/> For his research on the languages of [[Indonesia]], he received fellowships from the [[National Science Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chronicle.uchicago.edu/970612/awards.shtml  |title=Graduate students lead nation in Fulbright awards  |date= 1997-06-12 |work= University of Chicago Chronicle |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref> the [[Fulbright Program]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://chronicle.uchicago.edu/990610/fulbright.shtml |title=Graduate students receive the most Fulbrights  |date= 1999-06-10 |work= University of Chicago Chronicle |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref> and the [[Social Science Research Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://programs.ssrc.org/idrf/Fellows/1999 |title=International Dissertation Research Fellowships, 1999 Fellows |publisher= [[Social Science Research Council]] |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref> He was a Ford Foundation Fellow at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.international.ucla.edu/article.asp?parentid=2018 |author=Barbara Gaerlan |title=Benjamin Zimmer, 2002-2003 CSEAS Post-Doctoral Fellow |date=2002-08-26  |publisher= [[University of California, Los Angeles]] International Institute |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref> and taught at [[Kenyon College]] and [[Rutgers University]].<ref name=UChicago/>

In 2005, Zimmer was named a research associate at the Institute for Research in Cognitive Science at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] and became a regular contributor to [[Language Log]], a group weblog on language and linguistics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?author=8  |title=Author profile, Benjamin Zimmer  |work=[[Language Log]] |publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania]] |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref> He was named editor for American dictionaries at [[Oxford University Press]] in 2006,<ref>{{cite news |author=Andrew Adam Newman |title=How Dictionaries Define Publicity: The Word of the Year |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2007-11-10 |accessdate=2008-11-18 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/10/business/media/10oxford.html}}</ref> and the following year launched "From A to Zimmer," a weekly lexicography column on the OUP blog.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.oup.com/2007/06/corpus/ |author=Casper Grathwohl |title= It's Coming... An A To Zimmer Introduction  |date=2007-06-27  |work= OUPblog |publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref> 

In 2008, Zimmer was appointed executive producer of the Visual Thesaurus, an interactive reference tool from Thinkmap, Inc.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=77 |author=[[Mark Liberman]] |title= Producers, linguistic and otherwise   |date=2008-04-23  |work= [[Language Log]] |publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania]] |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thinkmap.com/news.jsp  |title=Editor for American Dictionaries at Oxford joins Visual Thesaurus Team  |date=2008-08-21  |publisher=Thinkmap, Inc. |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref> He edits the content of the online magazine of the Visual Thesaurus and writes a regular column on word origins entitled "Word Routes."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visualthesaurus.com/cm/wordroutes/1397/ |author=Ben Zimmer  |title="Procrastination": Let's Not Shilly-Shally!  |date=2008-05-13  |work=Word Routes |publisher= Visual Thesaurus |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref>
 
Zimmer's writing on language has appeared in two blog anthologies: ''Ultimate Blogs'' (Vintage, 2008, ISBN 978-0307278067)<ref>{{cite news |title=Permalinks |author=David Kamp |work=[[The New York Times Book Review]] |date=2008-03-23 |accessdate=2008-11-18|quote= |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/23/books/review/Kamp-t.html?ref=review }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nonfiction Reviews |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |date=2007-12-17 |accessdate=2011-05-23|quote= Benjamin Zimmer's 'Language Log' reads like a wonderfully expansive and more self-aware William Safire column. |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/1-legacy/16-all-book-reviews/article/10268-nonfiction-reviews-week-of-12-17-2007-.html }}</ref> and ''Far from the Madding Gerund'' (William, James, 2006, ISBN 978-1590280553).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wmjasco.com/0555/0555-front.pdf  |title=Introduction  |work=Far from the Madding Gerund |publisher=William, James |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://catdir.loc.gov/catdir/toc/ecip0610/2006008657.html  |title=Table of Contents, ''Far from the Madding Gerund'' |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref> He has also written for ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/?id=3944&qp=48150 |title= Articles by Ben Zimmer ||work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=2011-05-09}}</ref> and ''[[The Boston Globe]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Skadoosh! The story behind the word of the summer |author=Ben Zimmer |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=2008-06-29 |accessdate=2008-11-18|url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/ideas/articles/2008/06/29/skadoosh/ }}</ref> His research on word origins was frequently cited by [[William Safire]]'s "On Language" column for ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]''.

Zimmer serves on the Executive Council of the [[American Dialect Society]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americandialect.org/index.php/amerdial/2007/11/P3/  |title=Nominating Committee Report  |date=2007-11-01   |publisher=[[American Dialect Society]] |accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref> and chairs the society's New Words Committee.<ref name=UChicago/> He is also a member of the [[Dictionary Society of North America]].<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Gerald Marzorati]] |title=On Language With Ben Zimmer |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2010-03-21 |accessdate=2011-05-23 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/21/magazine/21edlet-t.html}}</ref>

On March 11, 2010, [[The New York Times Magazine]] announced the appointment of Zimmer as the new <U+201C>On Language<U+201D> columnist. Zimmer succeeded [[William Safire]], who was the founding and regular columnist until his death in late 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.businesswire.com/portal/site/home/permalink/?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20100311006834 |title=The New York Times Magazine Names Ben Zimmer as <U+2018>On Language<U+2019> Columnist |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=2010-03-11 |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> Zimmer's last "On Language" column was published on February 27, 2011. In it, Zimmer wrote that the column was "finally coming to a close ..." and that ..."it [was] time to bid adieu, after some 1,500 dispatches from the frontiers of language."  

==Family==
Benjamin is the brother of science writer [[Carl Zimmer]] and the son of former New Jersey congressman [[Dick Zimmer (New Jersey politician)|Dick Zimmer]].

